questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;will taught​&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this sentence, error lied in the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;will taught.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here we need&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;be&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;between&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;will&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;and&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;taught.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Will be + past participle&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is a passive voice.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;​&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;We will be met at the airport.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;/em&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;will taught​.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;​​&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Mathematics&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;will be taught &lt;/strong&gt;in his school by Rahul Sir.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;present tense&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the base form of the verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;do&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;does&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make questions with the present simple.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;does&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for the&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;third person singular (she/he/it)&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;do&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for the others.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use do and does with question words like&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;where, what&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;when.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Where do Angela and Rita live?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इस वाक्य में,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;will taught&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; वाक्यांश में त्रुटि है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;यहां हमें &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;will&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; और &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;ta&lt;/strong&gt;ught&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; के बीच&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;be&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; चाहिए।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;Will be + past participle&amp;quot;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;passive voice&amp;nbsp;है।
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;We will be met at the airport.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;3&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;on behalf of the railways&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is incorrect.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in part &lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;, i.e., &amp;quot;on behalf of the railways.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;on behalf of&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is used to mean &amp;quot;in the interest of&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;as a representative of,&amp;quot; which is not appropriate in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct phrase here should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by the railways&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; to indicate the agent causing the inefficiency and lack of good management.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;A lot of travel delay is caused due to the inefficiency and lack of good management &lt;strong&gt;by the railways&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;on behalf of&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is commonly used in formal communication to indicate representation, such as:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;She accepted the award on behalf of her team.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;We are writing this letter on behalf of the employees.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is used to indicate the agent or cause of an action, as in:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;The book was written by a famous author.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;The damage was caused by the storm.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;creation in the world&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, the usage of &amp;quot;creation&amp;quot; is incorrect instead of this we need to use &amp;quot;creations&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to grammar, whenever we use &amp;quot;one of&amp;quot; then, we need to use a plural noun after this because we are doing a selection from many hence, we need to use a plural noun after this phrase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Let&amp;#39;s see an example-
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He is one of the soldiers who fight for his&amp;nbsp;country.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;the correct sentence is-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Taj Mahal is one of the most beautiful&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;creations&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in the world.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Since the sentence refers to a period starting in the past and continuing to the present, the present perfect tense should be used.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;medicines have increased,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part C&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Due to the pandemic, the prices of &lt;strong&gt;medicines have increased&lt;/strong&gt; every day since last December.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is-&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(C).&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (C)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Either&lt;/strong&gt; means &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;both&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;one&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;neither &lt;/strong&gt;means&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;not either&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;none&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Either&lt;/strong&gt; is used in negative constructions, while &lt;strong&gt;neither&lt;/strong&gt; is used in affirmative constructions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Either and Neither&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are concerned with distribution between two things &amp;ndash;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;either is positive, neither is negative.&lt;/span&gt;​&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As the sentence already has a negative part&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;don&amp;#39;t&amp;#39;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;therefore we will use&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;either.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the use of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;neither&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;should be replaced by&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;either&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to make it grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(C).&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;I don&amp;#39;t have any money &lt;strong&gt;either&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(32, 33, 36);   &quot;&gt;A pronoun is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;a word that is used instead of a noun or noun phrase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(32, 33, 36);   &quot;&gt;Pronouns refer to either a noun that has already been mentioned or to a noun that does not need to be named specifically.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(32, 33, 36);   &quot;&gt;The main possessive pronouns are mine, yours, his, hers, its, ours, and theirs.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;त्रुटि वाक्य के&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (C)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;में है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Either&lt;/span&gt; का अर्थ है &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;#39;both&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;one&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; और Ne&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;ither&lt;/span&gt; का अर्थ है&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;#39;not either&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;none&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;Either&lt;/span&gt; नकारात्मक निर्माणों में उपयोग किया जाता है, जबकि Ne&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;ither&lt;/span&gt; सकारात्मक निर्माणों में उपयोग किया जाता है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Either and Neither&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;दो चीजों के बीच वितरण से संबंधित हैं -&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;either&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;सकारात्मक है,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;either&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;नकारात्मक है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;चूंकि वाक्य में पहले से ही एक नकारात्मक भाग&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;don&amp;#39;t&amp;#39; है, इसलिए हम either उपयोग करेंगे।&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इसलिए वाक्य&amp;nbsp;में&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;neither&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;के प्रयोग को&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;either&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;से बदल देना चाहिए ताकि वह व्याकरण की दृष्टि से सही हो।​&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;The feud escalated to the next generation as the fight over the family estate continued.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The original sentence is not correct, the preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;for&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is incorrect&amp;nbsp;in this context.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;over&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is more fitting in this context, as it implies conflict or competition for something specific. In this case, the family estate is object of the conflict, which justifies the use of &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;over&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The switch from &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;fighting&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; to &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;fight&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; in Option 2 and Option 3 makes the sentence more concise, and doesn&amp;#39;t alter the meaning, but Option 3 is more appropriate due to the change of the preposition.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the sentence &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;The feud escalated to the next generation as the fight over the family estate continued.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; correctly carries the meaning intended.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is- &amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Option 3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;: &amp;#39;escalates&amp;#39; is present tense and doesn&amp;#39;t match with the past tense &amp;#39;continued&amp;#39; later in the sentence. Furthermore, the preposition &amp;#39;about&amp;#39; is not suitable while referring to conflict or competition.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;: The use of &amp;#39;for&amp;#39; isn&amp;#39;t entirely wrong, but &amp;#39;over&amp;#39; better implies the sense of conflict and is thus a better choice.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;: The preposition &amp;#39;about&amp;#39; is not used in the context of conflicts. It is more commonly used to indicate the subject of a conversation or discussion, which does not match the intended meaning of this sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The erroneous part is: &lt;strong&gt;B.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the second&amp;nbsp;part of the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;singular&amp;nbsp;form of the verb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;plays&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, &lt;strong&gt;subjects &amp;#39;Taylor, Richard, and Francis&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; are &lt;strong&gt;plural&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the &lt;strong&gt;subjects are plural&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;verb should also be plural&lt;/strong&gt; (here, &lt;strong&gt;play&lt;/strong&gt;).
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;They &lt;strong&gt;play&lt;/strong&gt; basketball every weekend&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;plural&amp;nbsp;form of the verb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;play&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;in place of&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;singular form&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;plays&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Taylor, Richard, and Francis &lt;strong&gt;play&lt;/strong&gt; for the state basketball team&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;(a) One must take care of one&amp;#39;s health.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(b) Who they were I can&amp;#39;t say.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(c) My brother that is an school master is forty.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(d) Every member of the club was present.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Identify the sentence/s grammatically &lt;strong&gt;correct&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;3&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt; only (a), (b) and (d) are correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In sentence (a), the use of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;one&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;one&amp;#39;s&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is correct. It is grammatically consistent and correct: &amp;quot;One must take care of one&amp;#39;s health.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In sentence (b), the structure is informal but acceptable in English syntax: &amp;quot;Who they were I can&amp;#39;t say.&amp;quot; The clause &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Who they were&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; functions as the &lt;strong&gt;object &lt;/strong&gt;in the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In sentence (d), sentence structure and subject-verb agreement are correct. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Every&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is followed by a &lt;strong&gt;singular verb&lt;/strong&gt;: &amp;quot;Every member of the club was present.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In sentence (c), the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;that is an school master&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is grammatically incorrect. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;An&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;a&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;because the word &amp;quot;school&amp;quot; starts with a consonant sound.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct sentence should be: &amp;quot;My brother, who is a school master, is forty.&amp;quot; The relative clause &amp;quot;who is a school master&amp;quot; correctly identifies the noun &amp;quot;brother.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 3&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the second&amp;nbsp;part of the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;use of the verb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;help&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct form should be&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;helped&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; to match the &lt;strong&gt;past tense of the rest of the sentence.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Additionally, the phrase should be&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;helped me develop&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; instead of&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;help me developed&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;When I was in high school, I participated in several extracurricular activities such as the debate team and the school newspaper, &lt;u&gt;which helped me develop &lt;/u&gt;my communication and writing skills&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verbs in a sentence should be consistent in tense to maintain clarity and coherence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When referring to past events, ensure that all verbs are in the past tense unless a specific reason for a tense shift is required.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this case, since the activities and skills development occurred in the past, &amp;#39;helped&amp;#39; and &amp;#39;develop&amp;#39; are appropriate.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;No error&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, there is &lt;strong&gt;no error&lt;/strong&gt; in any part of the given sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;plural nouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(pesticides, fungicides) are &lt;strong&gt;correctly used as the subject&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We know that&amp;nbsp;if the&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;subject is plural&lt;/strong&gt;, its &lt;strong&gt;verb must also be plural&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;plural form of the verb &amp;#39;harm&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;correctly used with the plural subject&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the &lt;b&gt;subject and verb are agreeing with each other in number&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Chemicals such as pesticides&amp;nbsp;and fungicides harm&amp;nbsp;both honey bees and wild native bees&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Subjects and verbs must agree with one another in number&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;(singular or plural).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;if a subject is singular&lt;/span&gt;, its&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;verb must also be singular&lt;/span&gt;;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;if a&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;subject is a plural&lt;/span&gt;, its&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;verb must also be plural&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Option 2&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; i.e.&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;No error&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Let&amp;#39;s check all the segments of the given statement:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;The differences were&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;: The subject &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;differences&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is plural so the verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;were&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is plural.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;imperceptible to all but&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;: &amp;quot;To all but&amp;quot; is a phrase meaning &amp;quot;to everyone except.&amp;quot; It&amp;rsquo;s correctly used here.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;the most trained eye&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;: Here the use of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;the&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is correct because we use the before superlative degree. The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;trained&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; used as a participle is also apt.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the sentence is a &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;no error&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;construction.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct sentence is&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;The differences were imperceptible to all but the most trained eye.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;B&amp;#39;, i.e. the error lies in this part of the sentence.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the &lt;strong&gt;incorrect usage of prepositions&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;with&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;confident&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The adjective&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;confident&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; takes a fixed preposition &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;of&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; when we are confident about the ability or possibility of some event.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;To&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;here&amp;nbsp;needs to be replaced with&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;of&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore we will use &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Confident of&amp;#39;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also,&amp;nbsp;we will use&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;V1 + ing (gerund), noun, or pronoun&lt;/strong&gt; after all the&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;prepositions as &lt;strong&gt;each and every preposition &lt;/strong&gt;takes a&lt;strong&gt; prepositional object&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;But&lt;/strong&gt;, when a preposition is &lt;strong&gt;preceded &lt;/strong&gt;by an &lt;strong&gt;adjective &lt;/strong&gt;it takes a &lt;strong&gt;gerund &lt;/strong&gt;with it.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Mohit is &lt;strong&gt;confident of&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;passing &lt;/strong&gt;the exam.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct sentence will be:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;As I have practised&amp;nbsp;hard, I am &lt;strong&gt;confident of clearing&lt;/strong&gt; the cricket trials.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;/em&gt;Hence the error lies in part&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;B&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All the Prepositions take &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;V1 + ing&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; after them.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;He is &lt;strong&gt;afraid of going&lt;/strong&gt; alone at night.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;verb&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is used as a &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;noun&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;, the &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;ing&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;form of the verb is used, known as &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;gerund&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;Swimming&lt;/strong&gt; burns high calories.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;Option 2&amp;#39; i.e.&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;when a tree branch break the living room window.&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the verb tense of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;break&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct tense should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;broke&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;to maintain consistency with the &lt;strong&gt;past&lt;/strong&gt; tense narrative of the sentence (&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;was telling&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correction ensures that the action of the tree branch breaking the window aligns with the past continuous tense &amp;quot;was telling&amp;quot; used to describe Anant&amp;#39;s action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Other parts of the sentence do not contain errors and are correctly structured.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the complete correct sentence is- &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Anant was telling a story about his most recent exploits when a tree branch &lt;strong&gt;broke &lt;/strong&gt;the living room window.&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The error is in part&lt;strong&gt; (c) &lt;/strong&gt;of the sentence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;through&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; is used to indicate the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;means or method by which the gas turns into a liquid&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It clarifies that condensation is the process through which this transformation occurs.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct form should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;through a process called condensation&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;instead of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;from a process called condensation.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected sentence would be:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;(a) When a gas is (b) cooled down it turns into a liquid (c) through a process called condensation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect spelling of the word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;principles&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; It should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;principles&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;principals&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;Principals&amp;quot; refers to the heads of schools, whereas &amp;quot;principles&amp;quot; refers to fundamental truths or beliefs.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;he lived by the same principles&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 3&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;People admired him, for he lived by the same principles that he preached.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1: &amp;quot;that he preached.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2: No error&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in part 3.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;4: &amp;quot;People admired him, for&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;b&gt;B&lt;/b&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There is an error in &lt;strong&gt;part (b)&lt;/strong&gt;. The correct &lt;strong&gt;phrase&lt;/strong&gt; should be: &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;are converted into&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;phrase&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;are converted&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; describes an &lt;strong&gt;action that has been completed&lt;/strong&gt;, and it is followed by the &lt;strong&gt;preposition&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;into&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; which indicates the &lt;strong&gt;direction or result of the action&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;verb&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;convert&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to change in form, character, or function&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; and it is used to describe the process of changing one thing into another.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this case, the chemicals are being changed into new compounds through chemical reactions, so the &lt;strong&gt;past participle&lt;/strong&gt; form &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;converted&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is appropriate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;infinitive form&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to convert&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; describes an &lt;strong&gt;action that is yet to be completed&lt;/strong&gt;, which does not fit the meaning of the sentence in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;option 2&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The chemicals&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;are&amp;nbsp;converted&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;into&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;new compounds through chemical reactions.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;b&gt;Option 2)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;The cholera&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cholera is an uncountable noun and does not require an article (&amp;#39;the&amp;#39;) in this context.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, diseases are typically&lt;strong&gt; not preceded by the definite article &amp;#39;the&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Correct: Cholera is a frightful disease. Incorrect: The cholera is a frightful disease.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cholera &lt;/strong&gt;is a frightful disease.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Articles (&amp;#39;a&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;an&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;the&amp;#39;) are generally not used with uncountable nouns (like diseases, ideas, etc.).
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; Happiness is essential for a healthy life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When referring to specific, well-known entities or unique items, &amp;#39;the&amp;#39; is appropriate.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; The Sun rises in the East.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Common countable nouns require articles depending on their definiteness.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; A cat sits on the roof.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;much weekends&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;grammatically incorrect.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The erroneous part&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;much weekends&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be replaced with&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;many weekends&amp;#39;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;much&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;with&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;singular uncountable nouns&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;many&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;with&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;plural nouns&amp;#39;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example:
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;I haven&amp;rsquo;t got&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;much&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;change. I&amp;rsquo;ve only got a ten euro note.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Are there&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;many&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;campsites near you?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, in the given question, the word&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;weekends&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;quantifiable. And&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;weekends&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;a plural noun&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;also.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Option 2.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;So the correct sentence is-&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;There aren&amp;#39;t&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;many weekends&lt;/strong&gt; between now and Christmas.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;People that are lonely&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The error&lt;/strong&gt; in the sentence is in the first segment: &amp;quot;People that are lonely&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, we use &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;who&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; instead of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;that&amp;quot; when&lt;/strong&gt; we are referring to people.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;That&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is typically used when referring to things.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, while &lt;strong&gt;it&amp;#39;s not uncommon&lt;/strong&gt; to hear people use&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;that&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;when referring to people in casual conversation, it&amp;#39;s considered &lt;strong&gt;more correct &lt;/strong&gt;to use &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;who&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt; is : &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;People &lt;strong&gt;who &lt;/strong&gt;are lonely have higher levels of the hormone cortisol.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;with a vibrant mob of people&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence has an error in using the word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;mob&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;to describe&lt;strong&gt; the gathering of people&lt;/strong&gt;. While &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;mob&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; can refer to a disorderly or unruly crowd, it often carries a negative connotation and implies a group behaving aggressively or riotously.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected sentence would be: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The bustling market was filled &lt;strong&gt;with a vibrant crowd of people,&lt;/strong&gt; each person engaged in their own unique pursuits and interests.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Crowd&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; generally refers&lt;strong&gt; to a larger gathering of people in a particular place.&lt;/strong&gt; It doesn&amp;#39;t inherently &lt;strong&gt;imply disorder or negativity,&lt;/strong&gt; unlike the term &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;mob.&amp;quot; &amp;quot;Crowd&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is a more &lt;strong&gt;neutral and commonly&lt;/strong&gt; used word &lt;strong&gt;to describe a group of people gathered together.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;For example:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;A &lt;strong&gt;crowd of spectators &lt;/strong&gt;gathered to watch the parade.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The concert attracted a large&lt;strong&gt; crowd of music enthusiasts&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the sentence provided, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;crowd&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; accurately describes the gathering of people in the bustling market, conveying the sense of a lively and busy atmosphere without implying any negative or aggressive behavior.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The girls have tied&amp;nbsp;some luggages with a rope&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;i.e.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;this&amp;nbsp;sentence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;has an error&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the first option or sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;use of the plural form of the noun&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;luggages&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Uncountable nouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;usually&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;do not have a plural form&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;used with a singular verb&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;uncountable nouns&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;followed by a&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;singular verb&lt;/span&gt;)&amp;nbsp;that don&amp;#39;t take the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;articles&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;a/an&amp;#39;, many, few, and plural form.&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;​&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Luggage,&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;furniture, scenery, temper, hair, knowledge, equipment, pottery, music, jewelry, etc&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;For Example:&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;​The&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;sceneries&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;at my school&amp;#39;s library&amp;nbsp;enchanted me.&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/08/false%20%282%29.png&quot; style=&quot;font-weight: 700; white-space: pre-wrap; width: 25px; height: 25px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;scenery&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;at my school&amp;#39;s library enchanted me.&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/08/right%20%281%29.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 25px; height: 25px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;noun &amp;#39;luggage&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;in place of&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;luggages&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 1&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The girls have tied&amp;nbsp;some&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;luggage&lt;/strong&gt; with a rope&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;nouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;given below seem&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;plural&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in form but&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;in actuality&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;singular:&lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;News, billiards, summons, physics, measles, innings, etc&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;For Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​Physics is&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;an interesting subject.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The erroneous part is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;I know how hardest&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the superlative adjective &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;hardest&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;how&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; should be followed by a &lt;strong&gt;positive&amp;nbsp;adjective&lt;/strong&gt;, not a &lt;strong&gt;superlative adjective&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;how hard&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;, ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;option 3&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;I know how hard you have tried to fit in my shoes.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;coming lately at home&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is grammatically incorrect.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;late at home&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used instead of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;lately at home&amp;#39;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Both the word &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Late&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; and &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Lately&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; might seem similar but are different in meaning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Late&lt;/strong&gt; is both an &lt;strong&gt;adverb and an adjective&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;It means the opposite of &lt;strong&gt;early&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;The program started &lt;strong&gt;late&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lately&lt;/strong&gt; is also an adverb&amp;nbsp;it means &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;recently&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;He&amp;rsquo;s been studying hard &lt;strong&gt;lately&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, as per the points mentioned above, we find that the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	​&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Monika was reprimanded by her sister Hansa for &lt;strong&gt;coming late at home.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some words are used as both&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;adjectives and adverbs&lt;/span&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Daily, weekly, timely, monthly, early, fast, straight, outright, direct, hard, late, high, safe, quiet, etc.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Kapil takes the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;weekly&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;test for SSC-CPO.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Mark visits his family&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;weekly&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;that grows&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence discusses the lotus in the context of it being one of many beautiful flowers in the garden. Therefore, the verb should agree with the plural noun &amp;ldquo;flowers&amp;rdquo; rather than the singular &amp;ldquo;lotus&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &amp;ldquo;one of the most beautiful flowers&amp;rdquo; implies there are multiple beautiful flowers in the garden. Thus, the relative clause that follows should use &amp;ldquo;grow&amp;rdquo; instead of &amp;ldquo;grows&amp;rdquo; to maintain subject-verb agreement with the implied subject &amp;quot;flowers&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the sentence resides in the fragment &amp;ldquo;that grows,&amp;rdquo; which incorrectly uses the singular form of the verb &amp;ldquo;to grow.&amp;rdquo; To correct the sentence, &amp;ldquo;grows&amp;rdquo; should be changed to &amp;ldquo;grow&amp;rdquo; to properly align with the plural noun &amp;ldquo;flowers&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct sentence structure &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;One of the + Subject + Relative pronoun(who/that) + Plural Verb&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct sentence-&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The lotus is one of the most beautiful flowers that &lt;strong&gt;grow&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;in this garden.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;Option 2&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
